: "gene", "prob": 0.9973357319831848, "span": {"begin": 443, "end": 456}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7038"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Tg", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9999339580535889, "span": {"begin": 458, "end": 460}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007470"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "iodotyrosyls", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9496055245399475, "span": {"begin": 468, "end": 480}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7038"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Tg", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 492, "end": 494}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013974"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "thyroxine (T4)", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9702408313751221, "span": {"begin": 501, "end": 515}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014284"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "triiodothyronine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9971786737442017, "span": {"begin": 520, "end": 536}}], "text": "Thyroperoxidase (TPO) is a heme-containing apical membrane protein within the follicular lumen of thyrocytes that acts as the enzymatic catalyst for thyroid hormone (TH) synthesis (Taurog, 2005) across vertebrates. Two commonly used reference chemicals, propylthiouracil (PTU) and methimazole (MMI), are drugs that inhibit the ability of TPO to: a) activate iodine and transfer it to thyroglobulin (Tg) (Davidson et al., 1978); and, b) couple thyroglobulin (Tg)-bound iodotyrosyls to produce Tg-bound thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3) (Taurog, 2005).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:37:55 +0000 2026"}